The '''Kiltubbrid Shield''' is an [[Iron Age]] wooden shield from [[Ireland]]. It was discovered during the 19th century in the [[townland]] and parish of [[Kiltubbrid]], [[County Leitrim]], Ireland. It is probably the only perfect article of its description found in Europe,{{sfn|Wilde|1861|pp=492}} and dates from the [[La Tène culture|late Celtic (La Tène)]] period.{{sfn|Ridgeway|1901|pp=478}}
==Description== The Kiltubbrid shield is a remarkably well-preserved example of an ancient Irish wooden shield. It was discovered {{nobreak|in 1863}}, buried {{convert|3|m|1}} deep in a turf bog, at [[Kiltubbrid]] townland and just north of [[Lough Scur]].{{sfn|Coffey|1913|pp=75}} The shield is a perfect specimen, oval in shape, with a perfect central boss {{convert|7.6|cm|1}} high, and seven slightly raised concentric circles (ribs), plain on the reverse, with a handle, the whole carved out of one piece of wood.{{sfn|Wood-Martin|1895|pp=466}}{{sfn|Drummon|1871|pp=218}} The original measurements were {{convert|66|cm|1}} in height by {{convert|53|cm|1}} in width, with a thickness of {{convert|1.25|cm|1}}. Unlike ancient classic shields, through which the forearm was passed, the Irish wooden shield, grasped by the cross-piece underneath the umbo (boss), could be projected to full arm's length during battle.{{sfn|Wood-Martin|1895|pp=466}} The wood was probably [[alder]].{{sfn|Wilde|1861|pp=492}}{{sfn|Wood-Martin|1895|pp=466}}
<gallery class="center"> Killtubrid Shield Illustration.png|1st Illustration Kiltubrid-Alder-wooden-shield-Ireland.png|2nd illustration Kiltubrid-Alder-wooden-shield-Ireland2.png|3rd illustration Kiltubrid Shield Illustration.png|4th illustration </gallery>
The shields was probably covered with leather, painted and decorated.{{sfn|Wilde|1861|pp=492}}{{sfn|Wood-Martin|1895|pp=466}} The ribs show an indentation on one side, presenting a remarkable interruption in the symmetry of the ornament. Shrinkage may have caused the indentation.{{sfn|Wood-Martin|1895|pp=466}} MacAllister wondered if the indentation is a survival of the observation-notch which adorned shield edges in medieval time, or if this interruption of circular ornament reflected a widespread taboo and superstition against closed rings which prevailed at the time.{{sfn|MacAlliaster|1921|=p-171}}
==Etymology== [[Ruaidhrí Ó Flaithbheartaigh]] stated in Ogygia (1685) that the Irish name for alder was Fearn, because "shields are made of it". The Irish word ' sciath,' i. e. shield, is more recently applied to a shallow wicker basket, of oval shape — sometimes called a skib — ' used for straining potatoes, and which closely resembles in size and form of the Kiltubbrid wooden shield.{{sfn|Coffey|1913|pp=75}}{{sfn|Wilde|1861|pp=490}}
==Purpose== [[File:Irish Battle Scene Swords, Spears, and Shields.png|thumb|Irish Battle Scene Swords, Spears, and Shields]] The toughness and density of the alder would, in itself, be a firm defence against the thrusts of swords, if not spears,{{sfn|Wilde|1861|pp=492}} but half-inch thick wooden shields would be useless against Roman javelins.{{sfn|Drummon|1871|pp=218}}
An illustration sculptured on a stone cross at [[Kells, County Meath]] evidently depicts a conflict between different tribes or cultures; one armed with long-handled spears and circular bossed-shields, the opposing warrior shields have no boss, and are armed with short swords, of a kind often found on [[crannog]]s and first adopted with the introduction of iron as a primary material for weapons of warfare.{{sfn|Wood-Martin|1895|pp=467}}
